HEADWORD: Euroclydon
<hw>Eu*roc"ly*don</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr.
<?/; <?/ the southeast wind + <?/ wave, billow; according to another
reading, <?/, <it>i. e.</it> a north-east wind, as in the Latin Vulgate
<ets>Euro-aquilo</ets>.]</ety> <def>A tempestuous northeast wind which
blows in the Mediterranean. See <er>Levanter</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A tempestuous wind called <qex>Euroclydon</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Acts
xxvii. 14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
